n><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The appropriateness of academy status for </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">primary schools</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> and what special factors apply”</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Recommended as crucial for consideration in this inquiry are the contextual factors of rurality and size. It is vital to acknowledge how corresponding factors, such as limited available resources and geograp</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hical coherence in smaller rural primaries can limit the opportunities offered to them by academy status. The following concerns must be raised: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The lack of local alternative service providers available to academies in more rurally distributed areas.  </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Wit</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h fewer and less special</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ist resources, smaller primary academies</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in these areas</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">face</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> greater</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> difficulties in outsourcing the most competitive alternative providers less local to the area. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A solution previously offered by this committee of partnerships also faces complexities in this context. In rural areas, for example where primaries are more numerous and widely dispersed, this is a difficult solution to achieve strategically. The role of </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the LA could potentially evolve to </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">play a key role in coordinating the formation of </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">partnerships between primary academies in these areas. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Side-lined, yet also critical to this inquiry is the effect that greater academisation is having upon those schools </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that rely upon LA support. Reduced funding for non-academies that remain with the LA can leav</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e schools vulnerable and facing</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> closure or academisation. With smaller primaries most reliant upon LA support, this is a significant note of consideration</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on the a</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ppropriateness of academisation</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for this inquiry. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.0</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This submission is the product of extensive research that included contacting county councils, interviewing once council’s Assistant Director of Children’s Services, and analysing both com</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mittee reports and academy statistics at a regional and national level. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is compiled with the aim of raising schools standards and achievements in rural areas, where these can fall significantly below the national average. In my own county of Norfolk, r</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">esults and achievements have fallen to the extent where 40% of primaries were rated by Ofsted as “Less than good” in comparison to a national average of 31%</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> With the experience of attending an Academy in such a rural setting, it is my concern that the co</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mparative difficulties facing these smaller schools in rural areas are not relegated from the public agenda.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Raising standards through competition: the case of alternative service providers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Academy conversion </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">offers</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> schools the freedom to either continue purchasing services from their LA, or seek more competitive alternatives elsewhere. Yet, </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this freedom of choice </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has been</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> contextually limited. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Interviewing</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Assistant Director of Children’s Services from one Count</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y Council</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> absence of </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">alternative providers</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in rural areas</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was cited</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as evident</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> lack</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of competitive standards</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in these areas</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This could mean advantage</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of academy conversion </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> potentially stagnated</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in rural schools</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> when there is little comp</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etition</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or choice</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> between service providers from which to drive up standards.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">These schools can</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> face</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> alternatives of either: i) remaining</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to purchase services form the Lo</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cal Authority or ii) outsourcing</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to other providers less local to the area. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Conti</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nuing to purchase services from the LA can</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> potentially</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> problematise </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">efficiencies in provision </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">when LA standards are poor or below par. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Schools that comparatively choose to outsource service provision to a less local provider may face similar issues of effi</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ciency due to the lack of geographical proximity. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the context of small primary academies</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> without local alternatives</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, ii) </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a particularly ineffective solution. This is due to the great strategic capacity required to coordinate this service provision.  </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">With fewer resources in specialist staff and a reduced institutional capacity, </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> schools</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> may</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> face greater difficulty in ou</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tsourcing and maintaining the most competitive providers from more distant locations. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">If academy conversion is to be an effective solution for small</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> primaries in rural areas, there must be a sufficient range of local alternatives for the provision of s</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ervices.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This is particularly vital in instances where the Local Authority’s </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">quality and efficiency in services is of a poor standard.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The role of the LA in the formation of partnerships between schools</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.0</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Partnerships </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">frequently cited as</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> an effective solution for smaller schools lacking the resources required to outsource the most competitive providers.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whereby</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> encouraging</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> schools to pool resources together</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> may </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increase smaller schools’ institutional capacity and encourage greater </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">economies of scale to be achieved</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Yet, context is</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a prevalent issue for consideration here when some schools face greater difficulties than others in coordinating the formation of these partnerships.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 90pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In their previous inquiry into the effectiveness of p</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">artnerships for secondary schools alone, the committee recommended that those “In which all members are located in within close proximity are most likely to be effective”</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This concern of the committee </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is similarly prevalent to the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">case of primary academi</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">With</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a greater numeracy and more widely distributed location </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">across counties, issues of geographical proximity </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> potentially</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> exacerbated more greatly </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the context of</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> these</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> small, rural primaries. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The role of the Local Authority could be key t</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o coordinating efforts between these schools in the formation of effective partnerships. In a report on academy strategies, the Norfolk County Council noted the “considerable strategic capacity”</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; font-style:italic; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> required to encourage groups of primary s</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chools to set up t</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">heir own </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arrangements </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or form local partnerships</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. With the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">LA</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> needing to evolve to the recent conditions of academies within the educational landscape, a role of coordination could match the expertise </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> local knowledge of these authorities with the ability to increase educational standards. </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is particularly vital to smaller rural primaries, where the LA could </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">contribute to increasing their</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> institutional capacity by encouraging a pooling together of r</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">esources, expertise and knowledge between schools. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The impact of academisation on small primaries that rely upon LA support</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.4pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Relegated from the terms of this inquiry are the effects of academisation on the support framework of the LA. It is evident that </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increased academisation can significantly affect the ability of the LA to continue to fund those non-academies, with smaller primaries most at risk. If an LA is no longer required to provide non-statutory school support services to academies, they </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">risk rec</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eiving</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significant reduction in their</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> revenue grant. This could subsequently affect their ability to support financially those schools that remain under their provision.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.4pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.4pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is in particular those smaller primary schools that are at greatest risk from su</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bsequent issues of funding when they are the most reliant upon the LA for support for resources. The Lincolnshire County Council warned </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">previously</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of how the implementation of the current Academies policy could lead to 184 out of 276 primary schools being </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at risk of closure from a reduced revenue grant</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.4pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The pertinence of this issue in funding is reflected in how the LCC was subsequently forced to admit that it no longer had the financial capacity with which to fund those remaining schools under its suppo</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rt. That it recommended these schools’ conversion to academy status and </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">membership to</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a trust located hundreds of miles away demonstrates the clear failures in the funding system for Local Authorities. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.4pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> incident reflects two issues for consideration: 1) That the appropriation of funds to the Local Authority must be adjusted to account for the increased academisation of schools and separation from LA support 2) That rather than recommending smaller school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s to join trusts located miles away, the role of the LA would better be appropriated to use is local knowledge and expertise to coordinate local trust formations. With small rural primaries most at risk of reduced funding in LA support, this is a pertinent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> issue of consideration for this committee inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on the effects of the academisation process.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> “A good school for every Norfolk learne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">r”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline"> Report by the Director of Children’s Services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> (April 2013) </span><a href="http://www.norfolk.gov.uk/view/cabinet080413item14pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.norfolk.gov.uk/view/cabinet080413item14pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Telephone interview</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> with Assistant Director of Children’s Services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">onducted December 7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> 2013. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a nam